Forest Cover Classification

Initial Data Exploration

The dataset

This dataset contains observations of a selection of geographic data on 30 x 30 meter cells located in the Roosevelt National Forest of northern Colorado.
There are 581,012 observations of 12 independent variables.
The aim of this project is to develop a model that can accurately predict what type of forest cover a 30m x 30m cell in any area similar to the Roosevelt National Forest has, based on measurements of it's elevation; aspect; distance to water, roads and firepoints; hillshade; and soil type.

Independent variables were derived from data originally obtained from US Geological Survey (USGS) and USFS data.

Feature Type Measurement Description
Elevation Quantitative Meters Elevation in meters
Aspect Quantitative Azimuth Aspect in degrees azimuth
Slope Quantitative Degrees Slope in degrees
Horizontal Distance To Hydrology Quantitative Meters Horizontal distance to nearest surface water features
Vertical Distance To Hydrology Quantitative Meters Vertical distance to nearest surface water features
Horizontal Distance To Roadway Quantitative Meters Horizontal distance to nearest roadway
Hillshade 9am Quantitative ArcGIS index, 0 to 255 Hillshade index at 9am, summer solstice
Hillshade Noon Quantitative ArcGIS index, 0 to 255 Hillshade index at noon, summer solstice
Hillshade 3pm Quantitative ArcGIS index, 0 to 255 Hillshade index at 3pm, summer solstice
Horizontal Distance To Fire Points Quantitative Meters Horizontal distance to nearest wildfire ignition points
Wilderness Area1 Qualitative Boolean (4 one-hot columns) Wilderness area designation
Soil Type2 Qualitative Boolean (40 one-hot columns) Soil type designation
Cover Type3 Qualitative Integer, bewteen 1 and 7 Forest cover type designation

1 The set includes data from four wilderness areas located in the Roosevelt National Forest of northern Colorado. These areas represent forests with minimal human-caused disturbances, so that existing forest cover types are more a result of ecological processes rather than forest management practices.

  1. Rawah Wilderness Area
  2. Neota Wilderness Area
  3. Comanche Peak Wilderness Area
  4. Cache la Poudre Wilderness Area

2 The soil type is based on a USFS Ecological survey, and there are 40 distinct values. Each code in the dataset is associated with a USFS ELU Code and a description as per the table below. The first and second digits of the USFS ELU Code represent a climatic zone and geologic zone respectively.

First digit of USFS ELU Code: climatic zone

  1. lower montane dry
  2. lower montane
  3. montane dry
  4. montane
  5. montane dry and montane
  6. montane and subalpine
  7. subalpine
  8. alpine

Second digit of USFS ELU Code: geologic zone

  1. alluvium
  2. glacial
  3. shale
  4. sandstone
  5. mixed sedimentary
  6. unspecified in the USFS ELU Survey
  7. igneous and metamorphic
  8. volcanic

3 There are 7 distinct values for the cover type, each of which contains information on which tree species makes up the bulk of the forest cover for the area.

  1. Spruce/Fir
  2. Lodgepole Pine
  3. Ponderosa Pine
  4. Cottonwood/Willow
  5. Aspen
  6. Douglas-fir
  7. Krummholz

Cleaning, decoding, and categorising data


Although this stage of the process is meant for exploratory analysis only, there are some transformations that will assist both in creating and interpreting descriptive statistics and visualisations:

  1. Removing wilderness_area feature - the goal of the analysis is to develop a model that can predict cover_type for a 30m x 30m cell in any area similar to the Roosevelt National Forest, not only a cell in the one of the 4 specific areas in the forest from which the data was obtained. As such, the wilderness_area feature provides no explanatory value.
  2. Decoding the other one-hot encoded feature, soil_type, into a single column, with text values.
  3. Conversion of the aspect feature into text categories representing a cardinal direction ("n" for North, "se" for South East etc).
    While represented by integers, the feature is not accurately interpreted as an ordinal variable; e.g. an 45 degrees azimuth (north-east) is not lesser than 270 degrees azimuth (west).
  4. Conversion of integer label for soil_type and cover_type in to English

# Drop wilderness_area columns
drop_cols = ["wilderness_area_1", "wilderness_area_2", "wilderness_area_3", "wilderness_area_4"]
original_df.drop(drop_cols, axis=1, inplace=True)

# Decode soil_type columns
decoded_features = {"elevation":[], "aspect":[], "slope":[], "hor_dist_to_hydro":[], "ver_dist_to_hydro":[],
                    "hor_dist_to_road":[], "hillshade_9am":[], "hillshade_noon":[], "hillshade_3pm":[],
                    "hor_dist_to_fire":[], "cover_type":[], "soil_type":[]}
decoded_df = pd.DataFrame(decoded_features)

drop_cols = ["soil_type_1", "soil_type_2", "soil_type_3", "soil_type_4", "soil_type_5",
             "soil_type_6", "soil_type_7", "soil_type_8", "soil_type_9", "soil_type_10",
             "soil_type_11", "soil_type_12", "soil_type_13", "soil_type_14", "soil_type_15",
             "soil_type_16", "soil_type_17", "soil_type_18", "soil_type_19", "soil_type_20",
             "soil_type_21", "soil_type_22", "soil_type_23", "soil_type_24", "soil_type_25",
             "soil_type_26", "soil_type_27", "soil_type_28", "soil_type_29", "soil_type_30",
             "soil_type_31", "soil_type_32", "soil_type_33", "soil_type_34", "soil_type_35",
             "soil_type_36", "soil_type_37", "soil_type_38", "soil_type_39", "soil_type_40"]

for i in range(40):
    sub_df = original_df[original_df["soil_type_" + str(i + 1)] == 1].copy()
    sub_df.drop(drop_cols, axis=1, inplace=True)
    soil_type_list = [i + 1] * sub_df.shape[0]
    sub_df["soil_type"] = soil_type_list
    decoded_df = pd.concat([decoded_df, sub_df], axis=0)

decoded_df.reset_index(inplace=True, drop=True)
decoded_df = decoded_df.astype("int64")

Distribution visualisations

Visualisations of the dataset's features are plotted, initially independently of the target feature cover_type, and later split by cover_type.
The first set of visualisations assists in understanding each feature's overall distribution (helping to identify where scaling and normalisation will be required), and the second set of visualisations assists in understanding each feature's distribution with respect to the target (helping to judge association and predict which features might have high explanatory power in the future models).

In [9]:
# Interate through features
counter = 0
for feature in decoded_df.columns.tolist():

    # Determine feature type: quantitative or qualitative
    if decoded_df[feature].dtype == "int64":
        # Plot histogram
        plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (12,6)
        plt.figsize = (12,6)
        fig = plt.hist(decoded_df[feature], color=color_list[counter % len(color_list)])
        plt.title("Histogram of {}".format(feature))
        plt.show()
        counter += 1
        
    elif decoded_df[feature].dtype == "object":
        # Get list of unique values and the count of each
        chart_df = decoded_df[feature]
        value_counts = chart_df.value_counts()
        values = value_counts.index.values.tolist()
        count = value_counts.values.tolist()

        # Plot bar chart
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))
        ax.bar(values, count, color=color_list)
        plt.setp(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45, ha="right", rotation_mode="anchor")
        ax.set_title("Distribution of values for {}".format(feature))
        plt.show()

# Plot by cover_type
cover_type_list = sorted(decoded_df["cover_type"].unique().tolist())

for feature in decoded_df.drop(["cover_type", "soil_type"], axis=1).columns.tolist():
    
    # Determine feature type: quantitative or qualitative
    if decoded_df[feature].dtype == "int64":
        #Get averages
        avg_list = []
        for cover_type in cover_type_list:
            sub_df = decoded_df[decoded_df["cover_type"] == cover_type]
            avg_list.append(sub_df[feature].mean())
        # Plot bar chart
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))
        ax.bar(cover_type_list, avg_list, color=color_list)
        plt.setp(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45, ha="right", rotation_mode="anchor")
        ax.set_title("Average {}, by cover_type".format(feature))
        plt.show()
        
    elif decoded_df[feature].dtype == "object":
        # Get list of unique values, and the count that have each for each cover_type
        values = sorted(decoded_df[feature].unique().tolist())
        count_list = []         
        for cover_type in cover_type_list:
            sub_df = decoded_df[decoded_df["cover_type"] == cover_type]
            sub_list = []
            for value in values:
                sub_list.append(sub_df[sub_df[feature] == value].shape[0])
            count_list.append(sub_list)
        # Plot clustered column graphs
        x = np.arange(len(values))
        width = 0.13
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))
        offset = -3
        for i in range(len(cover_type_list)):
            ax.bar(x - (width * offset), count_list[i], width, label=cover_type_list[i], color=color_list[i])
            offset += 1              
        ax.set_title("Distribution of values for {}, by cover_type".format(feature))
        ax.set_xticks(x)
        ax.set_xticklabels(values)
        plt.setp(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45, ha="right", rotation_mode="anchor")
        ax.legend()
        fig.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

            sub_list = []

            ax.bar(x - (width * offset), count_list[i], width, label=cover_type_list[i], color=color_list[i])
            offset += 1                 
        ax.set_title("Distribution of values for soil_type ({} to {}), by cover_type".format(values[0], values[-1]))
        ax.set_xticks(x)
        ax.set_xticklabels(values)
        plt.setp(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45, ha="right", rotation_mode="anchor")
        ax.legend()
        fig.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

Distribution of target, as percentages


As it's clear that there is a very uneven distribution of values for the target variable cover_type, viewing what percentage of the total each makes up will provide context when measuring model accuracy. E.g. if a particular value makes up 60% of all observations of the target, then simply outputting that value in all future predictions would give a "default" predictive accuracy of 60%
Conversely, if a a particular value makes up only 1% of all observations, then a model could theoretically never predict that value and still be 99% accurate.

Measures of association

Measure of association between pairs of variables are calculated, and plotted on a heatmap.
Becuase there are two types of variable present, only measures of association between two variables of the same type can be calculated, and a different measure is required for each type:
association between two continuous variables is measured using a Pearson correlation coefficient,
association between two categorical variables is measured using Cramér's V

In [12]:
# Define a function  for calculating Cramer's V between two categorical pandas series
def cramers_v(series_1, series_2):
    cross_table = np.array(pd.crosstab(series_1, series_2, rownames=None, colnames=None))
    chi_2 = stats.chi2_contingency(cross_table)[0]
    observations = np.sum(cross_table)
    min_dimensions = min(cross_table.shape)-1
    return round((chi_2 / max(observations * min_dimensions, 1)), 3)

# Initialize and blank list and add to correlation dataframe for future recording of results

# Create a list of features
columns = decoded_df.columns.tolist()

#Initalize an empty list for recording results
association_list = []

# Iterate through columns
for x in columns:
    # Create an empty sub-list for later adding to the cramers_v_list
    sub_list = []
    feature_x = decoded_df[x]
    
    # Iterate again through columns
    for y in columns:
        
        # Calculate association based on datatypes of both features and add it to the sub-list.
        feature_y = decoded_df[y]
        
        if feature_x.dtype == "int64" and feature_y.dtype == "int64":
            association = round(stats.pearsonr(feature_x, feature_y)[0],3)
        elif feature_x.dtype == "object" and feature_y.dtype == "object":
            association = cramers_v(feature_x, feature_y)
        else:
            association = 0
        sub_list.append(association)
         
    # Add the sub-list to the cramers_v_list
    association_list.append(sub_list)
    
# Plot a heatmap of Cramer's V between each pair of features
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15, 15))
im = ax.imshow(association_list, cmap="RdYlGn")
ax.set_title("Heatmap of inter-feature correlation", fontsize=14)
ax.set_xticks(np.arange(len(columns)))
ax.set_xticklabels(columns, fontsize=12)
ax.set_yticks(np.arange(len(columns)))
ax.set_yticklabels(columns, fontsize=12)
plt.setp(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45, ha="right", rotation_mode="anchor")
for i in range(len(columns)):
    for j in range(len(columns)):
        association = association_list[i][j]
        c = "w" if abs(association) > 0.5 else "k"
        text = ax.text(j, i, association, ha="center", va="center", color=c, fontsize=12)
fig.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Observations

  1. There are no null values that require removal or filling
  2. The distribution of values in the target cover_type is unbalanced. This needs to be kept in mind in later phases, especially when choosing a metric for comparing models, creating train-test splits, and in choosing models and hyperparameters. Another option would be the Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique, or SMOTE, but it will not be used in this project.
  3. The distribution of many of the quantitative independent variables are skewed, so normalisation will be required.
  4. The quantitative independent variables have substantially differen scales, so scaling will be required.
  5. The data contains the horizontal and vertical distance to the nearest body of water, so the pythagorean distance to the nearest body of water can be calculated.
  6. The soil type USFS ELU Code contains 2 additional pieces of information, the climatic zone and geologic zone that might provide more explanatory power than the soil type itself.
  7. Categorial variables will need to be re-one-hot-encoded, and cover_type will need to be re-label-encoded.
